Rich,

Thanks for the explanation. Next question: I haven't heard any
discussion on either the time table for the IN-ADDR domain (RFC 921
only refers to converting programs that do host --&gt; addr mappings
by 5-15-85), or the exact partitioning of the IN-ADDR domain
into zones. The second question is significant because it directly
affects the way local administrators go about adding new hosts or nets to
the Internet; the name to address bindings can be handled in the
local zone/name server, but who is responsible for the inverse binding.
In other words, rather specific rules have been layed out regarding
the implementation of the name to address part of the domain heirarchy,
do the same rules govern the IN-ADDR domain? If my organization implements
the local zone for host names, does it also implement a zone for the
locally used class B and C networks?

Larry

